<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="618">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33947" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole punctatissima Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole punctatissima Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="618" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatissima">punctatissima</taxonomicName>
, very dotted with punctures, probably referring to the nearly complete foveolate sculpturing of the body.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="618">
diagnosis One of the most instantly recognizable of all 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24885" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole Westwood" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole Westwood" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="618" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pheidole</taxonomicName>
species: the major has a yellowish white posterior two-thirds of the head capsule (fading to pale yellow in older specimens) that contrasts sharply with the medium to dark brown remainder of the body; the major also is distinguished within the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33947" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole punctatissima Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole punctatissima Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="618" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatissima">punctatissima</taxonomicName>
group by the large area of rugoreticulation mesad to the eyes (see also 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181985" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole inca Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole inca Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="618" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inca">inca</taxonomicName>
) and the very prominent cornulate pronotal humerus and entire surface of the body foveolate and opaque. Minor: no carinulae on entire body, but all of the body parts except the second and succeeding segments of the gaster are foveolate and opaque.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="618">Measurements (mm) Major (Pueblo Nuevo, Mexico): HW 0.92, HL 0.92, SL 0.54, EL 0.14, PW 0.44. Minor (Pueblo Nuevo, Mexico): HW 0.44, HL 0.54, SL 0.50, EL 0.10, PW 0.24.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="619">Color Major: bicolorous, with posterior two-thirds of head surface, together with the lateral wings of the clypeus, yellowish white (fading to pale yellow in old specimens) and all the remainder of the body a sharply contrasting medium to dark brown; the first gastral tergite has bluish reflections; and the appendages exclusive of the mandibles are yellow. Minor: body concolorous medium brown, appendages except for mandibles brownish yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="619">
Range Tropical southern Mexico to Colombia. Literature records of the species from the West Indies are in error; they are based on the related species 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33621" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole bilimeki Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole bilimeki Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="619" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bilimeki">P. bilimeki</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:151496" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole punctatissima annectens Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole punctatissima annectens Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="619" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annectens">annectens</taxonomicName>
), q.v.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="619">
biology J. T. Longino (1997) on 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33947" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole punctatissima Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole punctatissima Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="619" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatissima">punctatissima</taxonomicName>
in Costa Rica: &quot;This species thrives in disturbed areas, and it is often a pest ant. Nests are often in ephemeral cavities; soft rotten sticks, beneath bark flaps, in debris in forks of trees, etc.&quot; In Mexico winged reproductives have been found in nests during April and July.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
